This is a spontaneous report from a contactable consumer who reported on behalf of a patient. A 29-month-old 
Black male patient started to receive ibuprofen (CHILDRENS ADVIL) suspension, orally, from 12Sep2013 at one 
tea spoon, two times a day for head cold. Ongoing medical history included included sneezing and cough, Ongoing 
concomitant medication included diphenhydramine hydrochloride (reported as KROGER BRAND CHILDREN'S 
ALLERGY) since an unspecified date at one teaspoon, once daily for sneezing and cough. The patient consumed 
more than the recommended dose of medication on 14Sep2013, elaborated as consumed about two extra tea 
spoons, due to which he felt sleepiness. Relevant laboratory data were none. The action taken in response to the 
events for ibuprofen was unknown. Therapeutic measures taken in response to the events were unknown. The 
outcome of the events was unknown. 
